Exaggerate: The claim exaggerates the impact of the election on the April 22 jump in COVID-19 cases.
Lack enough support: The claim lacks sufficient evidence to support the assertion that the election was the cause of the increase in cases.
Problematic assumption: The claim assumes a direct link between the election and the increase in cases without providing substantial evidence.
Exist alternative explanation: The expert suggests that the increase in cases on April 22 was due to a COVID-19 outbreak in Brown County, rather than the election.
Contradict fact: The claim contradicts the fact that there was no evidence at the time to support the claim that the election played a large role in the increase of cases.
Falters at times: The claim falters in providing a clear and supported argument for the relationship between the election and the increase in cases.
Understate: The claim may understate the impact of other factors, such as the outbreak in Brown County, in contributing to the increase in cases.
